      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "FEA vs. experimental compression-bending — primary QoI comparison",
      "description": "FEA-predicted construct stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm displacement were evaluated against the pooled experimental dataset (N=11) using the ASME V&V 10.1 area metric and a normalized validation error E/uval. All three QoIs returned E/uval values below 1.96 and percent differences below 10%, satisfying the pre-established acceptance criteria. The validation approach followed the protocol documented in Nagaraja et al. (2021), wherein model predictions from the FDA-developed Abaqus ensemble were assessed against physical bench constructs prepared per ASTM F1717 under static loading. Experimental scatter across the two laboratories was within 4.2% for stiffness and 6.8% for yield force, confirming inter-laboratory reproducibility. No systematic bias was identified in the residual distribution. The validation result is therefore considered satisfactory for the declared COU.",
      "validationMetric": "E/uval area metric (ASME V&V 10.1); percent difference on three QoIs",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "E/uval < 1.96; percent difference < 10% for all QoIs",
      "outcome": "All acceptance criteria satisfied; E/uval max = 1.41, max percent difference = 8.3%",
      "validationStatus": "assessed"
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/validation/secondary-comparator-cannulated",
      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "Cross-design plausibility check — cannulated construct historical data",
      "description": "As a supplementary plausibility check, FEA predictions for the non-cannulated construct were compared in trend against historical experimental data from a 7.5 mm cannulated pedicle screw construct tested under the same ASTM F1717 protocol in a prior study (Nagaraja et al. 2019). The cannulated design shares identical outer geometry and titanium alloy material with the non-cannulated variant; the only structural difference is the 2.5 mm central lumen. Stiffness predictions for the non-cannulated model exceeded the cannulated historical mean by 11.4%, consistent with the expected stiffness increase from solid cross-section geometry. This directional agreement was interpreted as supporting the credibility of the FEA framework. No formal acceptance metric was applied to this secondary comparison; it is presented as corroborating evidence only.",
      "comparedAgainst": "https://uofa.net/synth/data/nagaraja-2019-cannulated-historical-f1717",
